</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="405" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1624,2011]" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1732,1758]" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">Description.</emphasis>
First studied specimen from 
<collectingRegion box="[690,797,1733,1759]" country="Australia" name="Tasmania" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">Tasmania</collectingRegion>
(BL 
<quantity box="[862,953,1732,1759]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="405" unit="mm" value="5.2">5.2 mm</quantity>
) has radula 
<quantity box="[1100,1190,1733,1759]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="405" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
long with about 160 transverse rows of mature teeth and 11 gills per side arranged from valve 6 to anus. Second studied specimen from Sydney, Long Reef (BL 4.0 mm), a topotype, has radula 
<quantity box="[805,893,1804,1831]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="405" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
long with about 165 transverse rows of mature teeth. The topotype differs from the Tasmanian specimen by having more ribs (up to 17) on dorsal scales. The species is characterized by: 1. raised granules arranged in longitudinal rows in central areas of intermediate valves and in antemucronal area of tail valve and in a random manner in other areas (
<figureCitation box="[991,1057,1913,1939]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1903,1927]" captionTargetBox="[173,1403,519,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-165@2.[159,1429,505,1878]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Leptochiton badius, Northern coast of Tasmania, BL 7.0 mm, (ZISP 2382). A. Valve I, dorsal view; B. Valve II, dorsal view; C. Valve V, dorsal view; D. Valve VIII, dorsal view; E. Valve V, rostral view; F. Valve V, tegmentum sculpture in central area; G. Valve VIII, lateral view; H. Valve VI, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407807" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407807/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), 2. wide dorsal scales with wide bulbous base and 12–17 distinct, wide ribs (
<figureCitation box="[654,724,1949,1975]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1316,1340]" captionTargetBox="[176,1409,203,1265]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[159,1429,181,1293]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Leptochiton badius, Northern coast of Tasmania, BL 7.0 mm, (ZISP 2382). A, D. Dorsal, marginal and ventral scales and marginal needles; B. Dorsal scales; C. Dorsal scales and marginal needles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407811" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407811/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), 3. radula with small numerous narrow teeth and 4. tridentate cusp of major lateral tooth of radula (
<figureCitation box="[569,638,1985,2011]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[187,1403,1413,1936]" captionTargetId="figure-51@3.[172,1416,1401,1950]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Leptochiton badius, Northern coast of Tasmania, BL 7.0 mm, (ZISP 2382). A, B. Central portion of radula from anterior part." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407813" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407813/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="405">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
